Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Access Bank, Kakuzi, Kenya Airways

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-08-29T16:43:20Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-29/sub-saharan-african-stocks-access-bank-kakuzi-kenya-airways.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index rose 0.2
percent to 1,945.16 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .  Kenya ’s All-Share Index closed at its lowest in more than
19 months, falling 0.1 percent to 60.93 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index declined
for a seventh day, dropping 2.2 percent to 21,497.61 by the 2:30
p.m. close in Lagos, according to a statement on the bourse’s
 website . The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index fell the most
in more than four months, dropping 1.3 percent to 1,146.10 by
the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Access Bank Plc (ACCESS)  , a Nigerian lender, dropped to
the lowest since November 2009, falling 28 kobo, or 4.9 percent,
to 5.57 naira. The bank said it will seek shareholder approval
to buy 75 percent of Intercontinental Bank Plc, which was bailed
out by the central bank in 2009.  Kakuzi (KKZI)  Ltd, a Kenyan tea and fruit producer,
advanced to its highest in more than two months, gaining 3
shillings, or 4.3 percent, to 73 shillings. The company said
first-half net income increased to 85.3 million shillings
($911,000) compared with 82.8 million shillings a year earlier.  Kenya Airways Ltd. (KNAL)  , sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
biggest airline, rose for the first day in five, adding 50
cents, or 1.6 percent to 31.75 shillings. The airline plans to
buy additional aircraft to expand its flight network in Africa,
it said in an e-mailed statement today.  Mumias Sugar Co. (MSUG KN), Kenya’s biggest producer of the
sweetener, closed at its highest in almost three weeks, gaining
15 cents, or 2.4 percent, to 6.45 shillings. Analysts expect an
increase in world sugar prices to boost the company’s earnings
in the current financial year.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
